out 1230","Abt 1285":"about 1285","Abt 1284":"about 1284","1315":"1315","1248":"1248","Abt 1260":"about 1260","1335":"1335","1254":"1254","Weston-on-the-Green, Oxfordshire, England":"Weston-on-the-Green, Oxfordshire, England","North Weston, Oxfordshire, England":"North Weston, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","North Weston, Oxford, England":"North Weston, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","North Weston, Oxfordshire, England.":"North Weston, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Quartermain","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Quarterman  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Quarterman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Germaine, Marcel, Pascal.","English (Oxfordshire and Surrey): nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>quatre mayns</i>, <i>quatre mans</i> ‘four hands’, which has been taken to imply ‘mail-fisted’ but was perhaps used of a skilled craftsman or a dextrous juggler or conjuror."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Quartermain was born about 1230, in North Weston, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Herbert Quartermain, was 51